    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Rank-Order Merging Outperforms Score Merging"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When you combine results from multiple retrievers \u2014 BM25 for keyword matching and a dense vector retriever for semantic similarity \u2014 each system returns its own ranked list with incomparable scores. BM25 scores are TF-IDF-based floating-point numbers; cosine similarity scores from a dense retriever are bounded between -1 and 1 but still vary by model. You cannot simply average these scores. Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF) sidesteps this problem entirely by discarding scores and merging solely on rank position. A document ranked first by any retriever contributes \u22481/61 to the fused score; one ranked tenth contributes \u22481/70. Documents appearing near the top of multiple lists accumulate high fused scores and rise in the merged ranking."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "RRF diagram: BM25 and dense ranked lists merging via 1/(k+rank) formula",
          "title": "Reciprocal Rank Fusion"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The RRF Formula"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Given a set of ranked lists R and a constant k (default 60), the fused score for document d is the sum of reciprocal ranks across all lists that contain it:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "RRF(d) = \u03a3 ",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "1 / (k + rank_r(d))"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " for each list r \u2208 R that contains d"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The constant k=60 was empirically chosen by the original RRF paper (Cormack et al., 2009) to down-weight high-rank divergence between lists. It acts as a smoothing term: rank-1 gives 1/61\u22480.0164, rank-2 gives 1/62\u22480.0161, rank-60 gives 1/120\u22480.0083. The scores are small but their relative ordering is what matters after sorting."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementing RRF from Scratch"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The core implementation is a simple score accumulation loop. Each retriever contributes its ranked list; the function computes each document's contribution and aggregates across retrievers."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from collections import defaultdict\nfrom langchain_core.documents import Document\n\ndef reciprocal_rank_fusion(\n    ranked_lists: list[list[Document]],\n    k: int = 60,\n) -> list[tuple[Document, float]]:\n    \"\"\"Merge multiple ranked document lists using Reciprocal Rank Fusion.\"\"\"\n    scores: dict[str, float] = defaultdict(float)\n    docs_by_id: dict[str, Document] = {}\n\n    for ranked in ranked_lists:\n        for rank, doc in enumerate(ranked, start=1):\n            # Use page_content hash as a stable document ID\n            doc_id = doc.metadata.get(\"id\") or str(hash(doc.page_content))\n            scores[doc_id] += 1.0 / (k + rank)\n            docs_by_id[doc_id] = doc\n\n    # Sort by descending fused score\n    sorted_ids = sorted(scores, key=lambda d: scores[d], reverse=True)\n    return [(docs_by_id[doc_id], scores[doc_id]) for doc_id in sorted_ids]\n\n# Example: fuse BM25 and dense results\nbm25_results  = bm25_retriever.invoke(\"transformer attention\")\ndense_results = dense_retriever.invoke(\"transformer attention\")\n\nfused = reciprocal_rank_fusion([bm25_results, dense_results])\nfor doc, score in fused[:5]:\n    print(f\"{score:.4f}  {doc.page_content[:70]}...\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RRF with LangChain EnsembleRetriever"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LangChain's EnsembleRetriever wraps multiple retrievers and runs RRF automatically. The weights parameter controls how many results each retriever contributes, not a score weighting \u2014 internally EnsembleRetriever calls each sub-retriever, merges the ranked lists with RRF, and returns the fused top-k documents."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langchain.retrievers import EnsembleRetriever\nfrom langchain_community.retrievers import BM25Retriever\nfrom langchain_community.vectorstores import Chroma\nfrom langchain_openai import OpenAIEmbeddings\n\n# Build sub-retrievers\nembeddings = OpenAIEmbeddings()\nvectorstore = Chroma.from_documents(docs, embeddings)\ndense_retriever = vectorstore.as_retriever(search_kwargs={\"k\": 10})\n\nbm25_retriever = BM25Retriever.from_documents(docs)\nbm25_retriever.k = 10\n\n# weights controls the relative contribution from each retriever\nensemble = EnsembleRetriever(\n    retrievers=[bm25_retriever, dense_retriever],\n    weights=[0.4, 0.6],   # BM25 40%, dense 60%\n)\n\nresults = ensemble.invoke(\"how does attention mechanism work\")\nfor doc in results:\n    print(doc.page_content[:80])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Three or More Retrievers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RRF generalises naturally beyond two retrievers. Adding a third list \u2014 say, a multi-query sub-query retriever or a re-ranker that exposes a ranked list \u2014 costs only one extra loop iteration in the fusion function. Each additional retriever provides an independent relevance signal; documents that appear consistently near the top across all three lists receive the strongest boost."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langchain.retrievers.multi_query import MultiQueryRetriever\nfrom langchain_openai import ChatOpenAI\n\nllm = ChatOpenAI(model=\"gpt-4o-mini\", temperature=0)\n\n# Third retriever: multi-query sub-questions\nmulti_query = MultiQueryRetriever.from_llm(\n    retriever=vectorstore.as_retriever(search_kwargs={\"k\": 8}),\n    llm=llm,\n)\n\ndef fuse_three(query: str, top_n: int = 5) -> list[Document]:\n    bm25_res   = bm25_retriever.invoke(query)\n    dense_res  = dense_retriever.invoke(query)\n    multi_res  = multi_query.invoke(query)  # deduplicated internally\n\n    fused = reciprocal_rank_fusion([bm25_res, dense_res, multi_res])\n    return [doc for doc, _ in fused[:top_n]]\n\nresults = fuse_three(\"explain positional encoding in transformers\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Attaching RRF Scores to Metadata"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For debugging and downstream filtering it is useful to store the fused score and each retriever's original rank in the document metadata. This provenance data lets you diagnose why a document was promoted, tune k, and set minimum score thresholds."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from copy import deepcopy\n\ndef rrf_with_provenance(\n    ranked_lists: list[list[Document]],\n    retriever_names: list[str],\n    k: int = 60,\n    top_n: int = 5,\n) -> list[Document]:\n    \"\"\"RRF that records each retriever's rank in metadata.\"\"\"\n    scores: dict[str, float] = defaultdict(float)\n    provenance: dict[str, dict] = defaultdict(dict)\n    docs_by_id: dict[str, Document] = {}\n\n    for name, ranked in zip(retriever_names, ranked_lists):\n        for rank, doc in enumerate(ranked, start=1):\n            doc_id = doc.metadata.get(\"id\") or str(hash(doc.page_content))\n            scores[doc_id] += 1.0 / (k + rank)\n            provenance[doc_id][name] = rank\n            docs_by_id[doc_id] = doc\n\n    sorted_ids = sorted(scores, key=lambda d: scores[d], reverse=True)\n    result = []\n    for doc_id in sorted_ids[:top_n]:\n        doc = deepcopy(docs_by_id[doc_id])\n        doc.metadata[\"rrf_score\"] = round(scores[doc_id], 6)\n        doc.metadata[\"rrf_ranks\"] = provenance[doc_id]\n        result.append(doc)\n    return result\n\n# Inspect provenance\nenriched = rrf_with_provenance(\n    [bm25_results, dense_results],\n    [\"bm25\", \"dense\"]\n)\nfor doc in enriched[:3]:\n    print(doc.metadata[\"rrf_score\"], doc.metadata[\"rrf_ranks\"])\n# 0.032258 {'bm25': 1, 'dense': 2}\n# 0.032051 {'bm25': 3, 'dense': 1}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tuning k: Smoothing vs. Rank Sensitivity"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The k parameter controls how steeply rank differences are penalised. A small k (e.g. 10) makes rank-1 worth much more than rank-2 \u2014 the fusion heavily rewards top-ranked documents and ignores lower ranks. A large k (e.g. 200) flattens the curve so rank-1 and rank-5 contribute nearly equally, which favours documents with broad presence across all lists. The empirically validated default of 60 balances these extremes well for most RAG tasks."
          }
        ]
      },
