      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Deduplication Before Fusion"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the same document chunk appears in multiple retriever results, it should be treated as a single entry whose score accumulates across every appearance. Without deduplication, a document retrieved at rank 1 by BM25 and also at rank 3 by dense retrieval would be represented twice in the output list with two separate scores instead of one combined score. The fusion function must use a stable document identity key \u2014 either a metadata id field or a hash of the page content \u2014 to detect duplicates and sum their rank contributions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import hashlib\n\ndef stable_doc_id(doc) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Return a stable identity key for a document.\"\"\"\n    if doc_id := doc.metadata.get(\"id\"):\n        return str(doc_id)\n    # Fall back to SHA-1 of the first 512 chars of content (fast, collision-resistant enough)\n    return hashlib.sha1(doc.page_content[:512].encode()).hexdigest()\n\ndef rrf_deduplicated(\n    ranked_lists: list[list],\n    k: int = 60,\n    top_n: int = 5,\n) -> list:\n    scores = {}\n    docs_by_id = {}\n\n    for ranked in ranked_lists:\n        for rank, doc in enumerate(ranked, start=1):\n            doc_id = stable_doc_id(doc)\n            scores[doc_id] = scores.get(doc_id, 0.0) + 1.0 / (k + rank)\n            docs_by_id[doc_id] = doc  # last write wins; docs are identical\n\n    sorted_items = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)\n    return [docs_by_id[doc_id] for doc_id, _ in sorted_items[:top_n]]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RRF in a Full RAG Chain with LCEL"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LangChain Expression Language (LCEL) lets you wire the EnsembleRetriever directly into a RAG chain. The retriever runs RRF internally; the chain formats the fused documents into context and sends them to the language model. Because EnsembleRetriever implements the Runnable interface, it slots into any pipeline with no adapter code."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langchain_core.runnables import RunnablePassthrough\nfrom langchain_core.output_parsers import StrOutputParser\nfrom langchain_core.prompts import ChatPromptTemplate\nfrom langchain_openai import ChatOpenAI\n\ndef format_docs(docs) -> str:\n    return \"\\n\\n\".join(\n        f\"[{i+1}] {doc.page_content}\" for i, doc in enumerate(docs)\n    )\n\nprompt = ChatPromptTemplate.from_template(\n    \"\"\"Answer using only the provided context.\n\nContext:\n{context}\n\nQuestion: {question}\"\"\"\n)\n\nllm = ChatOpenAI(model=\"gpt-4o-mini\", temperature=0)\n\nrag_chain = (\n    {\n        \"context\": ensemble | format_docs,\n        \"question\": RunnablePassthrough(),\n    }\n    | prompt\n    | llm\n    | StrOutputParser()\n)\n\nanswer = rag_chain.invoke(\"how does self-attention compute token relationships?\")\nprint(answer)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Measuring RRF Recall Improvement"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "To quantify whether RRF fusion improves over each individual retriever, compare recall@k on a labelled evaluation set. Recall@k measures the fraction of relevant documents that appear in the top-k results. You typically see a 5\u201315% recall gain from fusion when BM25 and dense retrievers have complementary strengths \u2014 BM25 excels on rare keyword matches while dense retrieval excels on paraphrased or conceptually similar queries."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def recall_at_k(\n    query: str,\n    relevant_ids: set[str],\n    retriever,\n    k: int = 5,\n) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Compute recall@k for a single retriever or fused retriever.\"\"\"\n    results = retriever.invoke(query)[:k]\n    retrieved_ids = {stable_doc_id(doc) for doc in results}\n    hits = retrieved_ids & relevant_ids\n    return len(hits) / len(relevant_ids) if relevant_ids else 0.0\n\n# Evaluation harness\neval_set = [\n    {\"query\": \"how does attention work\", \"relevant\": {\"doc_1\", \"doc_5\", \"doc_9\"}},\n    {\"query\": \"positional encoding transformers\", \"relevant\": {\"doc_3\", \"doc_7\"}},\n]\n\nfor item in eval_set:\n    q, rel = item[\"query\"], set(item[\"relevant\"])\n    r_bm25   = recall_at_k(q, rel, bm25_retriever)\n    r_dense  = recall_at_k(q, rel, dense_retriever)\n    r_fused  = recall_at_k(q, rel, ensemble)\n    print(f\"Q: {q}\")\n    print(f\"  BM25={r_bm25:.2f}  Dense={r_dense:.2f}  Fused={r_fused:.2f}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "RRF merges ranked lists using ",
                    "marks": []
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "1/(k+rank)",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2014 no score normalisation required."
                  }
